definition.value: An ether lipid consisting of glycerol substituted at position 2 by an acetyl group and at position 1 by an unspecified alkyl group.
An ether lipid that is glycerol carrying a single alkyl substituent in an unspecified position.
A carboxamide resulting from the formal condensation of a carboxylic acid with the nitrogen of an indole.
A pyranone based on the structure of 2H-pyran-2-one and its substituted derivatives.
A quercetin O-glycoside that is quercetin attached to a beta-L-fucopyranosyl moiety at position 3 via a glycosidic linkage.
A L-fucoside with a beta-configuration.
A quercetin O-glycoside that is  quercetin attached to a alpha-D-rhamnopyranosyl moiety at position 7 via a glycosidic linkage.
Any rhamnoside that exists in the pyranose form and has alpha-D-configuration.
A phosphatidylglycerol that is the 3'-O-L-alanyl of any 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phospho-1'-sn-glycerol.
Any rhamnofuranoside that has alpha-L-configuration.
An L-rhamnofuranose having alpha-configuration at the anomeric centre.
A quercetin O-glycoside that is quercetin attached to a alpha-L-rhamnofuranosyl moiety at position 3 via a glycosidic linkage.
An O(4)-glycosyl-L-hydroxyproline that is cis-L-hydroxylproline glycosylated by a beta-L-Araf-(1->2)-beta-L-Araf-(1->2)-beta-L-Araf moiety
An amino acid zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of N(alpha)-methyl-L-histidine.
An iron molecular entity that is a compound or mineral containing iron and sulfur.
Any member of the class of iron sulfides in which the iron is in the (2+) oxidation state.
Any member of the class of iron sulfides in which the iron is in the (3+) oxidation state.
A member of the class of iron(3+) sulfides that has formula Fe2S3. A black powder, it decomposes at room temperature to give iron(2+) chloride, hydrogen sulfide, and sulfur.
A single-stranded DNA oligonucleotide comprised of one thymidine, one deoxyguanidine and two deoxycytidine residues connected by 3'->5' phosphodiester linkages in the sequence CTGC.
An arsenic molecular entity that is a compound or mineral containing arsenic and sulfur.
A monomethoxyflavone that is scutellarein methylated at position 6.
Any member of the class of arsenic sulfides in which the arsenic is in the (1-) oxidation state.
Any member of the class of arsenic sulfides in which the arsenic is in the (1+) oxidation state.
Any member of the class of arsenic sulfides in which the arsenic is in the (2+) oxidation state.
Any member of the class of arsenic sulfides in which the arsenic is in the (3+) oxidation state.
A double-stranded DNA fragment consisting of a 5'-CTGC-3' strand antiparallel to a 3'-GACG-5' strand.
A nucleobase-containing molecular entity that is a fragment of a larger double-stranded DNA molecule (either naturally occurring or synthetic).
A single-stranded DNA oligonucleotide comprised of one deoxycytidine, one deoxyadenosine and two deoxyguanosine residues connected by 3'->5' phosphodiester linkages in the sequence GCAG.
A monoalkylglycerol that is glycerol which is substituted by a (5Z,8Z,11Z,14Z)-icosa-5,8,11,14-tetraen-1-yl group at position 2.
A monoglyceride that is 1-oleoyl-sn-glycerol in which the hydroxyl hydrogen at position 2 is replaced by an arachidonyl group.

An oxo monocarboxylic acid that is benzophenone in which one of the phenyl groups is substituted by an amino group and a carboxymethyl group at position 2 and 3, respectively. The corresponding carboxamide, nepafenac, is a prodrug of amfenac and is used for the treatment of pain and inflammation following cataract surgery.
An oxo monocarboxylic acid anion resulting from the removal of a proton from the carboxy group of amfenac. The major species at pH 7.3.
An organic sodium salt having amfenac(1-) as the counterion.
A chromone that is 3-(1,3-benzothiazol-2-yl)-8-(1-piperidinylmethyl)chromen-4-one bearing additional ethyl and hydroxy substituents at positions 6 and 7 respectively.
The (R,R)-stereoisomer of 2-methyl-6-phytylhydroquinone.
The (R,R)-stereoisomer of 2,3-dimethyl-6-phytylhydroquinone.

A monocarboxylic acid amide that is amfenac in which the carboxylic acid group has been converted into the corresponding carboxamide. It is a prodrug for amfenac, used in eye drops to treat pain and inflammation following cataract surgery.
A 3-oxo monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 3-oxodecanoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A fatty acid ester obtained by condensation of the carboxy group of stearic acid with the hydroxy group of any alcohol or phenol.
A heteroaryl hydroxy compound that is 2-quinolone substituted at position 4 by a hydroxy group.
The R-enantiomer of 2-hydroxyhexadecanoate.
The S-enantiomer of 2-hydroxypalmitate.
An organic cation that is the conjugate acid of D-cycloserine, obtained by protonation of the amino group.
An organic anion obtained by deprotonation of the enolic hydroxy group at position 3 of any 3,4-didehydropyranoside. It is the major species at pH 7.3. (according to MarvinSketch version 16.1.18.0).
A steroid saponin that is avenacoside B lacking the 26-O-glucosyl residue.
A steroid saponin that is avenacoside A lacking the 26-O-glucosyl residue.
An O(4)-glycosyl-L-hydroxyproline that is cis-L-hydroxylproline glycosylated by a beta-L-Araf moiety.
A monocarboxylic acid that is acetic acid in which one of the methyl hydrogens is replaced by a 5,6-dimethyl-9-oxoxanthen-4-yl group.
